node.text: Mateo, 9 and Kaleb, 8 are a curious duo. They never stop asking questions. So their parents, director, @marvilacar and cinematographer, @benlowy decided to take their talkative boys on the road to meet with experts and learn about nature, cultures and everything else in between. In this episode, Mateo and Kaleb head to Isla Guadalupe to cage dive with Great White Sharks, as well as tag and study sharks with marine biologist, Dr. Craig O’Connell @thesharkdoctor . The boys experience the excitement and heartache that comes with witnessing the realities facing sharks. @dinnertableconversations

node.text:
We head away from land onto the ice floes of the Gulf of St. Lawrence with @bertiegregory, where thousands of harp seals are giving birth to tiny yellow pups. The adults have come so far south from their feeding grounds that this forms a unique oasis away from their main predator, the polar bear. But there’s a catch. From the minute the pups are born, they enter a race against time. In one of the shortest mammal weaning periods, the pups have just 10 days to drink all the milk possible and start swimming before their mothers abandon them on melting ice. Our changing climate means the stakes couldn’t be higher. If the ice melts before they learn to swim, this generation of pups will drown. 
The visuals are magical, with unbelievably cute pups peppered across the ice. This story is a unique opportunity to get up close and personal with ice, both above and below the surface. This episode will ultimately bring to life the message of the entire Wild_Life series: We are all inextricably tied to sea ice. Content Sponsored by @ExploreCanada.

node.title: WILD_LIFE Episode 5: The Harp Seal's Race Against Time

node.text:
In this episode we witness one of the Arctic’s most magical moments. With the help of a one-of-a-kind local tracker, @bertiegregory finds a female polar bear fresh out of her winter den with her tiny new cub. We see ultimate cuteness as the cub explores the world outside for the first time. Their irresistible interactions distract from the fact that the mother bear is actually making an impossible decision. The mother has spent the last eight months starving, so she is eager to rush to the ocean where she can hunt. But to reach the seal feast means a 40-mile trek. Does she wait to allow the cub to gain strength for the long trek, or does she head out to sea to make sure her milk doesn't dry up? 
We also follow a young female bear in her first moments of independence, having been kicked out by her mother. She has spent the last two and a half years with her mother preparing for this moment, but she quickly manages to get herself into trouble. Will she be able to survive a wolf on the hunt? Content Sponsored by @ExploreCanada.

node.text: Polar bears dominate the Arctic animal headlines; it’s hard for anything to escape their shadow. In this episode, @bertiegregory meets an unexpected array of smaller species that each have their own peculiar but no less entertaining strategies for surviving in this brutal environment. The tiny arctic fox might look cute, but it’s actually a killing machine. The arctic hare may be fluffy and have comical ears, but it’s both a master of camouflage and one of the fastest animals here. The snowy owl has sacrificed speed for a mightier secret weapon: silence. We find a lemming (a tiny brown rodent) running around in a blizzard, a big mistake when silent assassins are flying overhead. Although these unsung heroes are some of the few who’ve perfectly adapted to this place, the environment is changing fast. Warming temperatures are allowing enemies to move north, encroaching on these Arctic specialists. Content Sponsored by @ExploreCanada.

node.text: As autumn draws to a close, male polar bears converge at the coast for the “big freeze.” This annual event is hotly anticipated after a long summer spent starving on land. Now with the landscape’s imminent transformation, the bears will finally be able to reach their seal prey out at sea. While waiting, these thousand-pound animals turn to fighting each other. But these epic acts of aggression are not what you think. @bertiegregory’s close-up filming allows us to explore the fascinating and sometimes even tender rituals between males, while also showing the incredible adaptations that have allowed them to thrive in this harsh environment. When on foot with the world’s biggest land predator, you must always be on your guard. Bertie uses expert help with some surprising tactics to avoid becoming a hungry male’s next dinner. Content Sponsored by @ExploreCanada.

node.text: As the first snowfall of autumn arrives, @bertiegregory lands in the western Hudson Bay following a tip that a pack of gray wolves is hunting polar bears—an interaction that has never been filmed before and one that questions the notion of who is predator and who is prey.  Despite our historical demonization and extermination of wolves throughout much of North America, our intimate encounters with the wolves reveal how they’re surprisingly similar to us. Working together as a family with a fiercely loyal spirit, we see that pack living is key to their success. This strategy is what allows them to take on the Arctic’s top predator, who is many times their own weight. After some early success in filming them, the team loses the wolves in this vast territory. Will they achieve their ultimate goal of filming the whole pack on a hunt? Content sponsored by @ExploreCanada.

node.text:
Photo @jasonedwardsng - In Australia the Dingo is either revered or reviled. An intelligent and adaptable carnivore, their genetic diversity has dwindled because of out-breeding with domestic dogs. They are known to take livestock but often the culprits are mixed-breed dogs that have returned to wild pack behavior. Pure dingo lack the digestive enzymes to dissolve sheep fat and prefer small mammals and other native prey. 

I saw many ‘dingo’ carcasses whilst shooting this story and none of them were pure. Most did not exhibit any dingo characteristics and those that did for example their colour, had strong traits of domestic dog about them. Farmers struggling to maintain stock numbers need to remove the threat, however when controlling wild populations of native wildlife in any country, it’s best to target the source of the issue. People need to keep better control of their pets, especially at night, and not allow them to roam free when unnecessary breeding or predation may occur.

Please join me @jasonedwardsng for my upcoming book 'Icebergs to Iguanas' featuring my field assignments and National Geographic images.

#natgeowild #jasonedwardsng #australia #wilddog #dingo

node.text:
Photo @jasonedwardsng - Sharks are majestic, fascinating and a crucial link in the oceanic food chain. Research has determined that where shark populations are healthy, the populations of other fish species are also healthy, benefitting local community food resources and tourism revenue. 

Sadly, humans are systematically bringing nearly every shark species to the brink of extinction. Every time there is an interaction between humans and sharks the media goes into a frenzy and the shark suffers. I once heard you're more likely to be killed by a goat than killed by a shark. I've no idea if that is accurate, however I'll start getting worried when a mad scientist crossbreeds sharks with goats and they escape to the ocean!

Please join me @jasonedwardsng for my upcoming book 'Icebergs to Iguanas' featuring my field assignments.

#natgeowild #jasonedwardsng #sharkconservation #australia #sharks

They are a seemingly quiet species with cautious and yet elegant movements. That poise vanishes when they erupt in song, a raucous chorus of barks and howls.

Photo @jasonedwardsng - The ancient face of an endangered Green Sea Turtle after she finished depositing her eggs in a sand nest on a small coastal island. She was a late arrival to the beach, often a deadly scenario for these marine reptiles. The sun was high and hot by the time she had finished laying, however she crested the small dune and slid into the warm sea gliding off toward the horizon.

Photo @jasonedwardsng - African Elephants drink more than 200x litres of water every day. When dry season heat hangs over the landscape like a blast furnace they are desperate for water by the time the sun goes down. When the herds emerge from the thicket the calves need to keep up with their mothers as they hurry to dwindling water supplies.

Please join me @jasonedwardsng for my upcoming book 'Icebergs to Iguanas'.

Photo by @daisygilardini |  Ready for landing, a horned puffin approaches the grassy cliff on St. Paul Island in Alaska’s Pribilof Islands.
Photographing incoming puffins is a real challenge. Due to their heavy body and relatively short wings, puffins flap their wings extremely quickly: 400 beats a minute!
In order to freeze the action — light permitting — I like to shoot at at least 1/2500s. 
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories.

Photo by @amivitale / The baby orphaned elephants of Reteti Elephant Sanctuary in northern Kenya play with one another inside their enclosure. Reteti is the first ever community-owned elephant sanctuary in Africa. What’s happening at Reteti is nothing less than the beginnings of a transformation, not only in the way humans relate to wild animals but also how we relate to one another. This oasis where orphans grow up, learn to be wild so that one day they can rejoin their herds, is a story as much about the elephants as it is about all of humanity.

Follow @amivitale and @r.e.s.c.u.e to learn more, including how you can help.

node.text:
Photo by @DaisyGilardini / Seeing king penguins court is quite a show. To attract a partner, the males perform an ecstatic display, which includes  trumpeting calls while stretching their necks as far as they'll go.
If the female is responsive, the two will engage in a mutual display of stretching, cooing, bowing and bobbing heads.
If there are more than two birds, there may often be fierce fights, usually involving two males trying to impress a single female. Flapping and beaking — pecking at each other with their beaks — can be  intense, and last for hours.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories.

Photo by @amivitale / Baby orphaned elephants frolic in the mudhole at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) in northern Kenya. Adult elephants can be excellent swimmers and if faced with a strong current, they use their trunk as a snorkel and then march right across rivers 12 feet deep. Long ago people thought that ancestral elephants may have come out of the seas. A popular myth was that their trunk evolved as a kind of snorkel in more aquatic settings.

Photo by @journeying_justin / Deep in the Central Valley of Costa Rica - next to one of the largest cities in Central America, lives a special kind of frog that is threatened with extinction due to habitat loss and the use of pesticides. 

But thanks to the hard work of many conservation organizations and local landowners like @jardindelourdes and their head start programs and habitat expansion programs, these tree frogs have a hopeful future. 

This is the blue sided leaf frog (Agalychnis annae) and is known for their crazy cool neon blue sides, bright yellow eyes and award winning smile.

Follow @journeying_justin for more wildlife conservation stories. #natgeowild #natgeo

node.text:
Often seen resting on the rocky shores of the Galápagos Islands are the world’s only oceangoing lizards – the marine iguanas. 
Unlike the lizards on land, these reptiles have adapted well to the island life here. They can dive beneath the tides with their flattened tails and stream-lined bodies and forage on the marine algae on the ocean floor with their short snouts. Because they feed underwater, these island reptiles are also known for their very efficient salt glands, where they literally “sneeze” out the salt. Another incredible characteristic of these island lizards is their ability to stay underwater for more than 30 minutes. 
 
And also, they are extremely photogenic! 

To see more of my work on wildlife across the world, follow me @sandesh_kadur

Photo @jasonedwardsng - The power of Focus. 

It’s a misconception that only some lions will utilise trees. They’re cats, they climb! Whether to escape the insect hordes, catch a cool breeze, hide in the shade, or as in this case hunt nearby zebra. One of my philosophies is to always look up, the World doesn’t only exist immediately around me. Adding different perspectives to your stories creates variety and a narrative. 

And looking up in lion territory, especially when you’re on foot, is always a wise move! 

Please join me @jasonedwardsng for my upcoming book ‘Icebergs to Iguanas’ that features my National Geographic imagery.
